# Logging Standards

## Format

Use bracketed tags: `[Source] [Context]: Message | Details`

```javascript
// Good
console.log("[UserService] [fetch]: Retrieved user | id:", userId);
console.error("[PaymentService] [process]: Failed | error:", error);

// Bad
console.log("user fetched");
console.error(error);
```

## Log Levels

- **error**: Critical failures (database, API, unhandled exceptions)
- **warn**: Non-critical issues (deprecations, fallbacks, config warnings)
- **info**: Significant events (startup, auth, state changes)
- **debug**: Diagnostic details (function calls, variable values)

## Best Practices

✅ Include context (user ID, request ID)
✅ Log at service boundaries
✅ Include error stack traces
✅ Sanitize sensitive data
✅ Use appropriate log levels

❌ Don't log in loops
❌ Don't log passwords/tokens
❌ Don't use vague messages
❌ Don't log raw user data

## Sensitive Data

Never log:

- Passwords
- API keys/tokens
- Credit card numbers
- SSN/PII
- Session cookies

Sanitize before logging:

```javascript
const sanitized = {
	...data,
	password: undefined,
	token: undefined,
	cardNumber: "****" + data.cardNumber?.slice(-4),
};
console.log("[Service]: Data", sanitized);
```

## Error Logging

```javascript
try {
	await operation();
} catch (error) {
	console.error("[ServiceName] [operation]: Failed", {
		error: error.message,
		stack: error.stack,
		context: { userId, requestId },
	});
}
```

## Production

- Use logging library (not console.log)
- Add correlation/request IDs
- Integrate with log aggregation (Sentry, Datadog)
- Set up error rate alerts
- Extract performance metrics
